Social Media Analysis on LinkedIn Premium - Data Exploration, Visualization and Analysis¶

Group 3: Anh Phuong Ta, Xiaoyu Lyu, Aminaa Tserendagva, Minhua He, Anh Khoa Truong, Ying Cao, Pichsinee Kalklod, Yu Hsuan Wang, Yu Ching Chou, Thi Thuy Khue Nguyen, Kausalya Nandan Kolisetty.

INTRODUCTION¶

LinkedIn is a social networking platform used by professionals in the business community. The goal of the site is to enable registered members to establish and document networks of people they know and trust professionally. Additionally, LinkedIn serves as a valuable tool for job seekers, company research, and industry news updates. LinkedIn gathers data across users’ profiles to provide employers, workers and educators with data-driven insight into patterns that help align workforce supply with demand worldwide.

DATASET DESCRIPTION¶

For this proposal, our team worked hard to find a suitable dataset, one that will be able to help us provide suitable insights to our Milestone 1. After reviewing several datasets, we decided to use 2 of them:

  1. The first dataset is 'LinkedIn Job Postings - 2023', which has a total of 28 columns and more than 33,000 rows for different job postings in 2023. This dataset focuses on LinkedIn's job postings with columns such as: Job title, maximum salary, minimum salary, location, whether remote work is allowed, etc.
  2. The second dataset is 'LinkedIn Profiles and Jobs Data', which has a total of 27 columns with 10,000 rows, equivalent to 10,000 different companies' profiles on LinkedIn. This dataset focuses on LinkedIn's profiles with columns such as: Age estimate of the profile, company name, number of staff, etc.

Our team was divided into 2 smaller teams to work on these 2 datasets which aim to look at different types of possible visualizations for not only jobs posted on LinkedIn Premium but also the companies on the platform.

PROPOSAL OBJECTIVE¶

As mentioned above, we will walk you through all the steps that we took to analyze the two chosen datasets. We will also provide visualizations such as graphs to explain why it is necessary for LinkedIn Premium to implement them.

TOOLS USED¶

This proposal was completed using Python for all steps, including:

  1. Data Exploration
  2. Data Preprocessing
  3. Data Visualization
  4. Data Analysis

DATA VISUALIZATION - DATASET 1¶

We will walk you through various types of visualizations that is applicable for our first dataset, Job Postings. Linkedin Premium can utilize these ideas to add these graphs in for Premium members.

In [11]:
# @title Distribution of Work Types
# Count occurrences of each unique value in the 'formatted_work_type' column
work_type_counts = dataset1_new['formatted_work_type'].value_counts()

# Extract values and labels for the pie chart
values = work_type_counts.values
labels = work_type_counts.index

# Sort values and labels in descending order
sorted_indexes = sorted(range(len(values)), key=lambda i: values[i], reverse=True)
sorted_values = [values[i] for i in sorted_indexes]
sorted_labels = [labels[i] for i in sorted_indexes]

# Extract top 3 values and labels
top_3_values = sorted_values[:3]
top_3_labels = sorted_labels[:3]

# Create pie chart with only top 3 values and labels
plt.pie(top_3_values,
        labels=top_3_labels,
        autopct='%1.1f%%',
        colors=['Lavender', 'lightgreen', 'orange'],
        radius=1,
        textprops={"fontsize": 10})

# Set the title for the pie chart
plt.title("Distribution of Work Types", color="Blue", fontsize=16)

# Add legend
plt.legend(title="Top 3 Work Types", loc="upper right")

# Display the pie chart
plt.show()

According to our pie chart, the number of job postings that are for full-time hire exceeds 80%, for contract is 10.6% and for part-time positions only 6.9%. There are other types of employment in this dataset such as Volunteer and Internship but those numbers are less than 0% which is why they are not included in this pie chart.

Implementation: We believe LinkedIn Premium can show this pie chart for members who are seeking for employment. For example, if a Premium member is looking for an Internship for a specific role, LinkedIn can show the percentage on pie chart and give members the option of choosing different employment types.

In [12]:
# @title Top 10 Job Titles with Highest Maximum Salary

# We will group the job title with the max salary
job_title_max_salaries = dataset1_new.groupby('title')['max_salary'].max()

# Sort the salary in descending order so that we can get the top 10 values
job_title_max_salaries_sorted = job_title_max_salaries.sort_values(ascending=False)

# Save our top 10 salaries in dataset
top_10_max_salaries = job_title_max_salaries_sorted.head(10)

# Set a Seaborn color palette with virdis
colors = sns.color_palette('viridis', n_colors=len(top_10_max_salaries))

# Create a bar chart with imported colors
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
top_10_max_salaries.plot(kind='bar', color=colors, edgecolor='black')

plt.title('Top 10 Job Titles with Highest Maximum Salary', fontsize=16, color='darkblue')
plt.xlabel('Job Title', fontsize=14, color='darkblue')
plt.ylabel('Maximum Salary', fontsize=14, color='darkblue')
plt.xticks(rotation=90, ha='right', fontsize=10)
plt.yticks(fontsize=12)
plt.show()

According to this bar chart, we can see that the top 3 highest salary goes to Tech-related jobs.

Implementation: For example, when members applies for jobs, LinkedIn can provide a comprehensive page for these members that show the maximum salary, minimum salary, and maybe average salary for different job titles.

The heatmap illustrates the correlation coefficients between different numeric features. A correlation coefficient close to 1 indicates a strong positive correlation, while a coefficient close to -1 indicates a strong negative correlation. From the heatmap, we observe that:

  • Views and Applies have a strong positive correlation of approximately 0.88, indicating that job postings with higher views tend to receive more applications.
  • Views and Remote Allowed have a moderate positive correlation of approximately 0.34, suggesting that job postings with remote work allowance may attract more views.
  • Applies and Remote Allowed also show a moderate positive correlation, indicating that job postings with remote work allowance may receive more applications.
  • There are almost no correlation between Views, Applies, Remote_allowed and Sponsored, Max_salary, and Min_salary.
  • There is a strong positive correlation between Min_salary and Max_salary, we believe this is because if maximum salary increases, minimum salary will also increase.

In [20]:
def plot_nas(df: pd.DataFrame):
    if df.isnull().sum().sum() != 0:
        na_df = df.isnull().sum()
        na_df = na_df.drop(na_df[na_df == 0].index).sort_values(ascending=False)
        missing_data = pd.DataFrame({'Missing Ratio %' :na_df})
        missing_data.plot(kind="barh", legend=False, color = 'green')  # Specify plot type
        plt.xlabel('Number of NAs values')  # Add label for y-axis

        for index, value in enumerate(na_df):
            plt.text(value, index, str(value))  # Show number for each bar

        plt.show()
    else:
        print('No NAs found')

plot_width, plot_height = (9,4) # Adjusting plot figures
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (plot_width,plot_height)

plot_nas(dataset2)

We can see that there are a lot of Null values within our columns, however, this is unavoidable since we have more than 39,000 rows here. We have decided to drop all Null values and any potential duplicated values from all columns. After dropping, we still have about 33,000 rows left, meaning we only dropped less than 10% of the dataset, that is an acceptable percentage.

In [25]:
# @title Distribution of Company Staff Count
# Define the ranges for grouping
group_ranges = [(0, 100), (101, 500), (501, 1000), (1001, 5000), (5001, 10000)]

# Group the data based on the defined ranges
group_counts = []
for range_min, range_max in group_ranges:
    count = dataset2[(dataset2['Company Staff Count'] >= range_min) & (dataset2['Company Staff Count'] <= range_max)].shape[0]
    group_counts.append(count)

# Define labels for the pie chart
labels = [f'{range_min}-{range_max}' for range_min, range_max in group_ranges]

# Plot the pie chart
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.pie(group_counts, labels=labels, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=140)
plt.title('Distribution of Company Staff Count')
plt.axis('equal')  # Equal aspect ratio ensures that pie is drawn as a circle.
plt.gca().axes.get_xaxis().set_visible(False)  # Hide the x-axis tick labels
plt.gca().axes.get_yaxis().set_visible(False)  # Hide the y-axis tick labels
plt.show()

For this pie chart, we divided all the companies 5 groups:

  1. Companies with 0-100 employees
  2. Companies with 101-500 employees
  3. Companies with 501-1000 employees
  4. Companies with 1001-5000 employees
  5. Companies with 5001-10000 employees

Implementation: LinkedIn can consider using this for Premium members who are applying for jobs. On an average, usually a person applies to at least 10 to 100 jobs, so to have this visualization, members can know what their ideal company's size is based on their job applications.

# @title Correlation Heatmap for LinkedIn Profiles

numeric_columns = dataset2[['Age Estimate', 'Company Follower Count', 'Followers Count',

INSIGHTS SUMMARY¶

The insights below provide answers to the initial project objectives for this proposal:

  1. In the first dataset, 'LinkedIn Job Postings - 2023', we focus a lot on analyzing Job Postings on LinkedIn and found that most jobs on LinkedIn are for Full-time position.
  2. The top 3 highest salary are all related to Tech jobs, and all over $100,000.
  3. Most jobs on LinkedIn are for Med-Senior level and Entry level.
  4. The average age for LinkedIn members is 38, and most members are around 30 to 45 years old.
  5. A lot of companies on LinkedIn have less than 100 staff, meaning that companies are using the platform to reach more people.

Our team worked on 2 different datasets because we want to give LinkedIn the most thorough analysis on Data exploration, visualization and analysis for Premium features. We provided different graphs above to give LinkedIn the options of choosing the most suitable ones to implement for their members.

For example, the pie chart on dataset 2 can be used to show members their ideal company's size based on their job applications. Or the pie chart in dataset 1 is good to show what work types are available for a specific type of job title.
